observations.recommendation:
We recommended and the Management agreed that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant-Designate, in coordination with the Property/Supply Officer to investigate on the discrepancy noted, reconcile the amounts recorded in the books with the RPCPPE, and effect the necessary adjustments.

We reiterated our recommendations and the management agreed that the Municipal Mayor:

Create an Inventory Committee to fully conduct the physical count of all PPE and prepare and submit the complete RPCPPE to the Auditor not later than January 31 of the following year;

Require the Property/ Supply Officer to prepare and maintain the Property Cards for all PPE accounts; 

Direct the Municipal Accountant-Designate to determine the specific details of the undepreciated PPEs and recognize depreciation expense for all depreciable PPE items;

Avail of the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts as provided under COA Circular No. 2020-006 to finally establish PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition, and accountability.

We also recommended and the Management agreed that the Municipal Mayor direct the Property/Supply Officer to ascertain the status of the idle PPEs and recommend immediate repair or disposal, thereof, whichever is applicable.

xxx

Direct each office/ department of the Municipality to conduct inventory-taking and tagging using stickers with control numbers and record all PPE existing in their respective offices and same shall be validated by the Inventory Committee to facilitate the preparation of the property cards, PPE ledger cards and Inventory Report by the GSO, Municipal Accountant and Inventory Committee, respectively.

We recommended and the Management agreed that the Municipal Mayor direct the Municipal Accountant-Designate to:

Record the receipt and issuance of inventories under the appropriate inventory and expense accounts;

Ensure that the recognition of the expenses relative to the issuance of inventories are duly supported with SSMI accompanied by RIS; and 

Prepare the SLCs.


We also recommended and the Management agreed that the Municipal Mayor direct the Supply Officer to:

Ensure that issuances of inventory are supported with RIS and SSMI;

Conduct physical count of inventories semestrally to determine the undistributed/unconsumed items and prepare the RPCI which must be submitted to the COA Office not later than July 31 and January 31 of each year for the first and second semesters, respectively; 

Prepare and maintain the SC; and

Prepare the RSPI and RPCSP as well as the other prescribed forms, registry and reports to strengthen controls over the semi-expendable properties pursuant to COA Circular No. 2022-004.

We recommended and the Management agreed that the Municipal Mayor instruct the Municipal Accountant-Designate and HRMO to:

Initiate the establishment of policy and guidelines in the selection, recruitment and remuneration of JO and COS personnel;

Specify the duties and functions of each personnel in the JO Contract, as well as the duty hours to be rendered by the JO personnel; 

Submit the basis or justification on the hiring of JO personnel beyond the six months limit of JO contract;

Include in the JO contract the provision on the claims for traveling expenses of the JO personnel; 

Submit justification on the payment for the services of JO personnel on days not covered by their contract; 

Submit the lacking DTR of the JO personnel and the list of the student beneficiaries of the BERT project of the Municipality. Henceforth, ensure that payment for the services of JO personnel are adequately documented; and

Indicate in the Accomplishment Report the quantified and specific duties and functions accomplished during the period.

We recommended and the Management agreed that the Municipal Mayor instruct the MENRO-Designate and personnel concerned to:

Provide assistance to the barangays in the management of their solid wastes;


Refrain from collecting unsegregated wastes from the barangay MRFs and establish the RCA for final segregation of residual wastes before disposal to the sanitary landfill contracted by the Municipality;

Intensify the IEC campaign on SWM and educate the constituents of the waste segregation at source;

Address the lack of manpower and personnel in-charge of the implementation of the SWM Program;

Initiate waste diversion strategies through recycling, composting by utilizing the bio-composter and expedite the operations and utilization of the Centralized MRF; and

Reconstitute and re-organize the Municipal SWM Board in order to monitor the full implementation of the Solid Waste Management Program of the Municipality.

We recommended the Municipal Mayor direct:

The concerned municipal officials and employees to liquidate and/or refund immediately their unliquidated cash advances;

The Municipal Accountant to ensure that no cash advances shall be allowed to any official or employee unless the previous cash advance granted is liquidated; 


The Municipal Accountant to look into the details of the negative balances included and effect the necessary correction to accurately record the balance of the unliquidated cash advances.

The LCE to direct the imposition of appropriate sanctions for the unjustified failure of the concerned Municipal officials and employees to liquidate their cash advances; 

The LCE to direct the Municipal Accountant-Designate and Municipal Treasurer to reconcile their records relative to the grant, utilization and liquidation of cash advances and prepare necessary adjusting entries to correct the balances of unliquidated cash advances;

The LCE to direct the concerned Municipal officials to follow the guidelines and procedures set in COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016 on the write-off, if warranted, of the unliquidated cash advances which have been long outstanding/ remained dormant in the books of accounts; and

The LCE to direct the conduct of an investigation and take appropriate action on the ORs issued by the Municipal Treasurer, representing refunds to settle her outstanding cash advances, which were dated December 17, 21 and 29, 2015, but appeared accomplished only after several ORs with various dates for the month of February 2016 were issued.

We reiterated our recommendations and the Municipal Mayor agreed to:
Create an Inventory Committee to fully conduct the physical count of all PPE and prepare and submit the complete Report on Physical Count of Property, Plant and Equipment (RPCPPE) to the Auditor not later than January 31 of the following year;
Require the GSO/Property Custodian to hasten the preparation and maintenance of the Property Cards (PC) all PPE accounts;
Direct the Municipal Accountant-Designate to determine the specific details of the PPE accounts by preparing a PPE ledger cards, conduct reconciliation with the GSO/Property Custodian, and make necessary adjusting entries on the discrepancies noted, if any;
Address the lack of manpower in the Accounting Department in order to expedite the preparation of the accounting reports; and
Avail of the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts as provided under COA Circular No. 2020-006 to finally establish PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition, and accountability.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to direct the following:
Municipal Accountant-Designate and OIC-Municipal Treasurer to verify and adjust the discrepancies noted and reconcile the cashbooks and accounting records regularly so that cash account balances are accurately presented in the financial statements;
Municipal Accountant-Designate to prepare the BRS within ten (10) days after receipt of the bank statements and submit the same monthly to the Audit Team pursuant to Section 74 of PD No. 1445 and COA Circular No. 96-011;
OIC-Municipal Treasurer to maintain the cashbooks for all active bank accounts of the Municipality and certify the monthly ending balances; and
OIC-Municipal Treasurer to verify the details of the dormant bank accounts and recommend its closure, if warranted.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to instruct the Municipal Accountant-Designate to:
Submit the detailed schedule of Accounts Payable as of 
December 31, 2023 and other documents to support the claims against government funds;
Prepare adjusting entries for the noted variance between the amount recorded in the disbursements and the recognized Accounts Payable, erroneous recording of the unpaid claims of the officers and employees of the Municipality and erroneous recording of retention money withheld from various contractors, as specified in Annexes B and C;
Adhere to the provision of Sections 141, 145 and 151, Volume II of the MNGAS for LGUs in the recognition of the unpaid claims of the Municipality as of year-end and the retention money deducted from the progress billings of various contractors; and
Adhere to the provisions of Section 4 of P.D. No. 1445 and the pertinent provisions of the NGAS Manual for LGUs relative to the supporting documents necessary in the recording of Accounts Payable of the Municipality.

We recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to direct the following:
OIC-Municipal Assessor to fast track the processing of the Certificates of Title of the 26 parcels of land owned by the Municipality to establish absolute ownership and protect the interest of the Municipality over those lots;
Municipal Accountant-Designate to reconcile and maintain Real Property Ledger Cards for the land account, and correct the records of land properties of the Municipality, if warranted;
Concerned personnel to conduct an inquiry as to the evidence of ownership of the Municipality over the parcels of land reported as Municipality’s property, and provide for a central file for the pertinent titles/documents thereto;
Municipal Accountant-Designate to recognize in the books the land donated to the Municipality; and
GSO/Property Custodian to ascertain the actual use of land owned by the Municipality by conducting a physical inspection and to maintain Property Cards thereto.
We further recommended and the Municipal Mayor agreed to update the Audit Team of the status of the case over the contested lots of the Municipality.

We recommended the following:
a. The Municipal Treasurer to account for all her undeposited collections and deposit the same with the Authorized Government Depository Bank (AGDB); and
b. Henceforth, the concerned accountable officers to deposit all collections intact and in full amount with the authorized depository bank in accordance with the policies and procedures under PD No. 1445, COA Circular No. 92-382 and DOF-BLGF Local Treasury Operations Manual;
c. The Municipal Treasurer to update and accomplish properly her cashbooks by providing the complete details of references, and shall be reconciled regularly with the accounting records, at least once every quarter;
d. The Municipal Accountant - Designate, Municipal Treasurer and Designated Liquidating Officer to reconcile their records and effect necessary corrections, if any, to present the correct balances of the Cash Local Treasury in the financial statements;
e. The Municipal Accountant-Designate to maintain subsidiary ledgers for the accounts of all collecting/accountable officers and reconcile these with their records regularly.
We also recommended the conduct of an investigation and take appropriate action on the issuance of ORs with various dates in December 2015 but appeared accomplished only after several ORs were issued in February 2016.
(AAR 2015-2019)

We recommended that the LCE direct the following:
a. The Municipal Accountant-Designate to prepare the BRS within 10 days after receipt of bank statements and submit the same monthly to the Auditor pursuant to Section 74 of PD No. 1445 and COA Circular No. 96-011;
b. The Municipal Accountant-Designate and Municipal Treasurer to ensure coordination between their offices for timely submission of all the necessary documents to facilitate the proper and regular preparation of the BRS that will support the Cash in Bank balances. (AAR 2015-2019)

We recommended that the LCE direct the Municipal Treasurer to maintain the cashbook in accordance with the LTOM and submit the required reports, specifically the following:
a. Cashbook indicating the references of the posted transactions, updated balances daily, closed and ruled every month’s account and transactions, and accomplished certification;
b. Ensure that the balances obtained are reconciled with the cash on hand;
c. Present her duly accomplished Cashbook for Cash Advances for examination; and
d. Submit the CRAAF, together with the RAAF of all collecting and liquidating officers, to the Auditor for monitoring of the receipts and issuances of accountable forms.
